# Portolan atlas harness

When mapping, explaining, auditing, or navigating a local codebase or multi-repo
landscape:

1. Use the target-local wrappers installed under `<target-root>/.portolan/bin`.
   If they are missing, resolve the user-provided Portolan source first. A
   local checkout can be used directly; a URL must be fetched only after the
   user approves fetching exactly that URL into a local cache. Then run:
   `<resolved-portolan-path>/scripts/portolan-install.sh <target-root> --harness cursor --bundle-dir <bundle-dir>`
   Default `<bundle-dir>` to `<target-root>/.portolan/atlas` unless the captain
   supplied an explicit safe override.
2. Run doctor first and report blockers before building:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-scan.sh --doctor <target-root> <bundle-dir> --skip-install --no-viewer`
   The doctor must report target shape, bundle writability, tool availability,
   rough size, and local-first/no-network expectations.
3. If the user asks what will happen, show the dry-run plan:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-scan.sh --dry-run <target-root> <bundle-dir> --skip-install --no-viewer`
4. Build the atlas bundle:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-scan.sh <target-root> <bundle-dir> --yes --skip-install --no-viewer`
5. Remove `--skip-install` only after explicit operator approval to install
   missing local OSS tools.
6. Run bundle status after the scan:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-scan.sh --status <target-root> <bundle-dir>`
7. Read `<bundle-dir>/receipt.json` and
   `<bundle-dir>/captain-atlas-scorecard.json` after the scan. Preserve
   producer gaps, local-first flags, duration, first useful captain insight,
   next actions, and the viewer launch command in the handoff.
8. Generate and read the deterministic Q&A/drill-down artifact:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-query-eval.sh --run <bundle-dir>`.
   Include `<bundle-dir>/captain-qna-eval.json` status in the handoff.
9. Build and read the captain handoff artifact:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-captain-handoff.sh <bundle-dir>`.
   Use `<bundle-dir>/captain-handoff.md` as the human summary and keep
   `<bundle-dir>/captain-handoff.json` as machine-readable run status.
10. Query the bundle at answer time with
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-bundle-query.sh`
   instead of loading the full bundle into chat.
   Start with `repos`, `relationships`, `hotspots`, and `gaps`; use `search`,
   `symbol`, `source`, and `selected-code` for drill-down when indexes or
   selected paths exist.
11. Open the viewer when the user needs navigation:
   `<target-root>/.portolan/bin/portolan-viewer.sh`.
12. Cite bundle record ids or source paths and preserve `unknown`,
   `cannot_verify`, and `not_assessed`.

Do not require `go install` unless the user asks for the legacy Go path.
